{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567320"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:59:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:59:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18960"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18960"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.01,0.94,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104121"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11694"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86442"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11402"},{"type":"tags","id":"11403"},{"type":"tags","id":"11405"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27514"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104121"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman is diagnosed with breast cancer. She has decision-making capacity and understands the implications of treatment. She completes an advance care directive stating that she wishes to refuse chemotherapy and instead pursue alternative therapies, despite understanding this decision may shorten her life.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate ethical and legal response to this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Require psychiatric evaluation before accepting refusal","Override her wishes since chemotherapy offers the best chance of survival","Declare her lacking capacity due to this decision","Respect her right to refuse treatment","Seek a court order to mandate treatment"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct response is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erespect her right to refuse treatment\u003C/strong\u003E. Adults with decision-making capacity have the fundamental legal and ethical right to refuse medical treatment, even if healthcare providers disagree with their decision or if the decision may result in death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect responses can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequire psychiatric evaluation before accepting refusal\u003C/strong\u003E - Psychiatric evaluation is not required when a capable patient makes an informed choice\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverride her wishes since chemotherapy offers the best chance of survival\u003C/strong\u003E - Forcing treatment on a capable patient who has refused it would constitute assault and battery\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeclare her lacking capacity due to this decision\u003C/strong\u003E - Disagreeing with medical advice does not itself indicate lack of capacity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeek a court order to mandate treatment\u003C/strong\u003E - Courts generally uphold the right of capable adults to refuse treatment\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare providers should ensure the patient understands the consequences of refusing treatment, document the discussion thoroughly, and continue to offer supportive care while respecting the patient\u0027s autonomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients with decision-making capacity have the legal right to refuse medical treatment, even if that decision may result in death.","Advance care directives are legally binding documents that specify a patient\u0027s wishes for future medical care when they lose decision-making capacity.","Healthcare providers must respect valid advance care directives even if they disagree with the patient\u0027s choices."],"references":["Australian Government. Advance care directive. [online]. 2024. [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/topics/palliative-care/planning-your-palliative-care/advance-care-direc...","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86442"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18960"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86442"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T13:18:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T13:18:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11694"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104121"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt